Non parametric tests in R

Piotr Wieczorek

2023-06-14

  • Goal of this project
  • Wilcoxon test - 2 dependent groups
  • Mann U-Whitney test: 2 independent groups
  • Kruskal - Wallis - at least 3 independent groups
  • Dunns test - in order to evaluate differences between groups
  • Friedmans ANOVA - at least 3 dependent groups

Goal of this project

The aim of this project is to demonstrate various non-parametric tests using the gapminder dataset as an example. Following tests will be conducted:

  1. the Wilcoxon Signed Rank test

  1. the Mann U-Whitney test (otherwise known as the Wilcoxon Sum Rank test)

  1. the Kruskal Wallis test (with post hoc Dunns test)

  1. Friedmans ANOVA 

library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
library(rstatix)
library(png)
library(ggpubr)
library(gapminder)
df <- gapminder
unique(df$year)
##  [1] 1952 1957 1962 1967 1972 1977 1982 1987 1992 1997 2002 2007

Wilcoxon test - 2 dependent groups

HO: Median life expectancy in Europe in 2002 = Median life expectancy in Europe in 2007

Ha: Medians are not equal

df1 <- df %>%
  filter(year %in% c(2002,2007),
         continent %in% c("Europe")) %>%
  select(1,2,3,4)
head(df1)
## # A tibble: 6  4
##   country continent  year lifeExp
##   <fct>   <fct>     <int>   <dbl>
## 1 Albania Europe     2002    75.7
## 2 Albania Europe     2007    76.4
## 3 Austria Europe     2002    79.0
## 4 Austria Europe     2007    79.8
## 5 Belgium Europe     2002    78.3
## 6 Belgium Europe     2007    79.4
df1 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=lifeExp))+
  geom_density()

LifeExp doesnt follow normal distribution

shapiro.test(df1$lifeExp)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df1$lifeExp
## W = 0.93935, p-value = 0.005063
df1 <- df1%>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(year))
df1 %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(median_life_exp = median(lifeExp))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   year  median_life_exp
##   <fct>           <dbl>
## 1 2002             77.5
## 2 2007             78.6
df1 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year,y=lifeExp))+
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)+
  geom_jitter()+
  labs(title = "Life Expectancy in Europe in 2002 and 2007")

wilcox_test(data=df1,formula = lifeExp ~ year,paired = TRUE)
## # A tibble: 1  7
##   .y.     group1 group2    n1    n2 statistic             p
## * <chr>   <chr>  <chr>  <int> <int>     <dbl>         <dbl>
## 1 lifeExp 2002   2007      30    30         0 0.00000000186

Sum of all positive ranks = 0, meaning that each lifeExp in 2007 was higher than in 2002.

Conclusion: at p-value < 0.05 there is a proof to reject the null hypothesis.

Mann U-Whitney test: 2 independent groups

hypotheses:

H0: Median life expectancy in Europe in 2007 = median life expectancy in Asia in 2007

Ha: Medians are not equal 

df2 <- gapminder
df2<-df2 %>%
  filter(continent %in% c("Europe","Asia"),
         year == 2007) %>%
  mutate(year=as.factor(year)) %>%
  mutate(continent = as.factor(continent)) %>%
  select(1,2,3,4)
levels(df2$year)
## [1] "2007"
table(df2$continent)
## 
##   Africa Americas     Asia   Europe  Oceania 
##        0        0       33       30        0
df2$continent <- droplevels(df2$continent)
table(df2$continent)
## 
##   Asia Europe 
##     33     30
df2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=lifeExp))+
  geom_density()+
  facet_wrap(~continent,scales="free")

shapiro.test(df2[df2$continent=="Europe",]$lifeExp)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df2[df2$continent == "Europe", ]$lifeExp
## W = 0.92333, p-value = 0.03274
shapiro.test(df2[df2$continent=="Asia",]$lifeExp)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df2[df2$continent == "Asia", ]$lifeExp
## W = 0.92228, p-value = 0.02119
df2
## # A tibble: 63  4
##    country                continent year  lifeExp
##    <fct>                  <fct>     <fct>   <dbl>
##  1 Afghanistan            Asia      2007     43.8
##  2 Albania                Europe    2007     76.4
##  3 Austria                Europe    2007     79.8
##  4 Bahrain                Asia      2007     75.6
##  5 Bangladesh             Asia      2007     64.1
##  6 Belgium                Europe    2007     79.4
##  7 Bosnia and Herzegovina Europe    2007     74.9
##  8 Bulgaria               Europe    2007     73.0
##  9 Cambodia               Asia      2007     59.7
## 10 China                  Asia      2007     73.0
## #  with 53 more rows
df2 %>%
  group_by(continent) %>%
  summarise(median_life_exp = median(lifeExp))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   continent median_life_exp
##   <fct>               <dbl>
## 1 Asia                 72.4
## 2 Europe               78.6

Mann-Whitney U statistic formula

ggplot() + 
    background_image(readPNG("images/mann.png"))

df2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=lifeExp))+
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)+
  geom_jitter()+
  labs(title="Life Expectancy in Asia and Europe in 2007")

mann_whitney <- wilcox_test(data=df2,formula = lifeExp ~ continent, paired = FALSE)
mann_whitney
## # A tibble: 1  7
##   .y.     group1 group2    n1    n2 statistic         p
## * <chr>   <chr>  <chr>  <int> <int>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 lifeExp Asia   Europe    33    30       196 0.0000194

p-value = 1.94e-05 indicates that we should reject H0. It indicates that median life expectancy for Asia and Europe is different.

Kruskal - Wallis - at least 3 independent groups

hypotheses:

H0: Median life expectancy in Europe in 2007 = Median life expectancy in Asia in 2007 = Median life expectancy in Americas in 2007

Ha: at least one pair doesnt exhibit equal medians 

df3 <- gapminder
table(df3$continent,df3$year)
##           
##            1952 1957 1962 1967 1972 1977 1982 1987 1992 1997 2002 2007
##   Africa     52   52   52   52   52   52   52   52   52   52   52   52
##   Americas   25   25   25   25   25   25   25   25   25   25   25   25
##   Asia       33   33   33   33   33   33   33   33   33   33   33   33
##   Europe     30   30   30   30   30   30   30   30   30   30   30   30
##   Oceania     2    2    2    2    2    2    2    2    2    2    2    2
df3<-df3 %>%
  filter(continent %in% c("Europe","Asia","Americas"),
         year == 2007) %>%
  mutate(continent = as.factor(continent),
         year = as.factor(year)) %>%
  select(2,3,4)
df3$continent <- droplevels(df3$continent)
table(df3$continent)
## 
## Americas     Asia   Europe 
##       25       33       30
df3
## # A tibble: 88  3
##    continent year  lifeExp
##    <fct>     <fct>   <dbl>
##  1 Asia      2007     43.8
##  2 Europe    2007     76.4
##  3 Americas  2007     75.3
##  4 Europe    2007     79.8
##  5 Asia      2007     75.6
##  6 Asia      2007     64.1
##  7 Europe    2007     79.4
##  8 Americas  2007     65.6
##  9 Europe    2007     74.9
## 10 Americas  2007     72.4
## #  with 78 more rows

Kruskal Wallis statistic formuala

ggplot() + 
    background_image(readPNG("images/kruskal_wallis.png"))

df3 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=lifeExp))+
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)+
  geom_jitter()+
  labs(title="Life Expectancy by Continent in 2007")

kruskal_test(data=df3,lifeExp~continent)
## # A tibble: 1  6
##   .y.         n statistic    df         p method        
## * <chr>   <int>     <dbl> <int>     <dbl> <chr>         
## 1 lifeExp    88      21.6     2 0.0000202 Kruskal-Wallis

Conclusion: p-value = 2.02e-05. The null hypothesis should be rejected.

Dunns test - in order to evaluate differences between groups

dunn_test(data=df3,formula=lifeExp~continent)
## # A tibble: 3  9
##   .y.     group1   group2    n1    n2 statistic          p     p.adj p.adj.sig
## * <chr>   <chr>    <chr>  <int> <int>     <dbl>      <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>      
## 1 lifeExp Americas Asia      25    33    -0.864 0.388      0.388     ns         
## 2 lifeExp Americas Europe    25    30     3.31  0.000923   0.00185   **         
## 3 lifeExp Asia     Europe    33    30     4.46  0.00000804 0.0000241 ****       
## #  with abbreviated variable name p.adj.signif

Significant differences in median in groups:

  • Americas:Europe

  • Asia:Europe

Friedmans ANOVA - at least 3 dependent groups

hypotheses:

H0: Medians across all groups are equal

Ha: at least on pair of comparisons doesnt exhibit equal median 

df4 <- gapminder
df4 <- df4 %>%
  filter(continent == "Europe",
         year %in% c(1997,2002,2007)) %>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(year))
table(df4$year)
## 
## 1997 2002 2007 
##   30   30   30
df4 <- df4%>%
  select(1,2,3,4)
df4
## # A tibble: 90  4
##    country                continent year  lifeExp
##    <fct>                  <fct>     <fct>   <dbl>

##  2 Albania                Europe    2002     75.7
##  3 Albania                Europe    2007     76.4
##  4 Austria                Europe    1997     77.5
##  5 Austria                Europe    2002     79.0
##  6 Austria                Europe    2007     79.8
##  7 Belgium                Europe    1997     77.5
##  8 Belgium                Europe    2002     78.3
##  9 Belgium                Europe    2007     79.4
## 10 Bosnia and Herzegovina Europe    1997     73.2
## #  with 80 more rows
df4$id <- rep(seq(1:30),each=3)

Friedmans ANOVA statistic

ggplot() + 
    background_image(readPNG("images/friedman_formula.png"))

df4 %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  summarise(median_life_exp = median(lifeExp))
## # A tibble: 3  2
##   year  median_life_exp
##   <fct>           <dbl>
## 1 1997             76.1
## 2 2002             77.5
## 3 2007             78.6
df4 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year,y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_jitter()+
  labs(title="Life Expectancy in Europe by Year")

friedman.test(df4$lifeExp,df4$year,blocks = df4$id)
## 
##  Friedman rank sum test
## 
## data:  df4$lifeExp, df4$year and df4$id
## Friedman chi-squared = 54.2, df = 2, p-value = 1.701e-12

Based on p-value < 0.05, we should reject the H0.
